  "prompt": "What are good, low-cost (or free) alternatives to Google Alerts?",
  "response": "There are several good alternatives to Google Alerts that are low-cost or free, allowing you to monitor specific topics, keywords, or mentions across the web. Here are some of the best options:\n\n1. **Talkwalker Alerts**: This free service allows you to set up alerts for specific keywords and receive updates via email. It covers news sites, blogs, forums, and more.\n\n2. **Mention**: While it has a paid plan, Mention offers a free tier that allows you to monitor a limited number of sources for specific keywords. It's great for tracking brand mentions and industry news.\n\n3. **Feedly**: Although primarily an RSS feed aggregator, Feedly can be used to follow specific blogs, websites, and news sources for updates on topics of interest. You can create alerts based on feed updates.\n\n4. **BuzzSumo**: BuzzSumo offers some free features, such as tracking brand mentions and finding popular content. While its full capabilities are within paid plans, you can still extract valuable insights from the limited free version.\n\n5. **IFTTT (If This Then That)**: This automation tool allows you to create \"applets\" that monitor certain keywords or topics on various platforms and send notifications via email, SMS, or other channels.\n\n6. **Social Search Engines**: Use platforms like Social Search, Followerwonk, or Social Mention to track keywords on social media and forums. While they may vary in functionality, they often provide valuable insights.\n\n7. **Alerti**: This is another monitoring tool that offers keyword tracking across various sources. It has both free and paid plans, with the free plan offering basic alert capabilities.\n\n8. **Scoop.it**: This content curation tool can help you follow specific topics and create your own curated feed. You can get updates on selected topics and share them with others.\n\n9. **Feedbin**: While not free, it\u2019s a relatively low-cost RSS reader service that allows you to follow websites, blogs, and other sources for updates.\n\n10. **Newsletters**: Subscribing to newsletters from relevant blogs or websites in your industry can also provide curated content updates directly to your inbox.\n\nThese options can help you stay informed without relying solely on Google Alerts. The best choice will depend on your specific needs and preferences.",
